Chapter 7. Analysis of function: Sentence Modes

Analyses from PhD Thesis on Phonology and Phonetics of Derry City English Intonation

Antion Eoin Rodgers, Phonetics and Speech Laboratory, Trinity College Dublin

This page contains all analyses conducted in R for Chapter 7 of my PhD thesis on the phonology and phonetics of intonation in Derry City English (DCE). This particular chapter focuses on describing the intonation associated with sentence mode (declarative statements, wh-questions, yes-no questions and declarative questions).

There are are two key aims in this chapter. One is simply to provide a description of intonation and sentence mode in DCE within the Autosegmental Metrical (AM) framework. The other is theoretical and aims to assess the viability and descriptive efficiency of an AM analysis which includes a separate register tier alongside the tonal tier.

Chapter 7.5: Phonological Analysis

7.5.1 Non-register-tier Analysis

Raw Data

tot_rows <- nrow(m_corpus)

Utterance Phonology (most common)

m_corpus %>%
  mutate(phr_phon = factor(phr_phon, levels = unique(phr_phon))) %>%
  filter(phr_phon %in% keep_list$phr_phon) %>%
  group_by(mode, phr_phon) %>%
  summarise(phon_count = n(), .groups = "rowwise") %>%
  arrange(desc(phon_count)) %>%
  mutate(phr_phon = str_replace_all(
    phr_phon,
    "(\\*)", "\\\\\\1"
  )) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = mode,
    values_from = phon_count,
    values_fill = 0
  ) %>%
  select(phr_phon, MDC, MWH, MYN, MDQ) %>%
  rowwise(phr_phon) %>%
  mutate(total = sum(c_across())) %>%
  tibble::rowid_to_column("#") %>%
  rename("Phonology" = phr_phon) %>%
  formattable(
    align = "r",
    caption = paste(
      "Utterance level intonational phonology by mode ",
      "for tokens accounting for at least ",
      percent(threshold / tot_rows),
      " of all tokens.",
      sep = ""
    ),
    list(
      area(col = 3:6) ~ proportion_bar(color = c(
        rep(brewer.pal(4, "Pastel2")[3], nrow(.)),
        rep(brewer.pal(4, "Pastel2")[2], nrow(.)),
        rep(brewer.pal(4, "Pastel2")[1], nrow(.)),
        rep(brewer.pal(4, "Pastel2")[4], nrow(.))
      )),
      total = proportion_bar(color = "#aaaaaa")
    )
  )

Adjusted Data

The raw data is unbalanced since there number of utterances per target speaker varies slightly. For some speakers, there are no repetitions of some target utterances. Therefore, the data has been adjusted to project an estimated balanced number of tokens per speaker per target utterance.

Firstly a tibble is created summarising the proportion of pitch accents per mode per speaker. This is done in three initial stages:

  1. Count the number of phonological tokens per stimulus per speaker.
  2. Convert the counts to proportion per stimulus per speaker.
  3. Convert the proportion per stimulus per speaker proportion per stimulus per mode.

From this table to summary tables are created:

  1. pitch accents per speaker (adjusted)
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token per speaker.
    2. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per speaker.
  2. pitch accents per speaker (adjusted):
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token per mode.
    2. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per mode
  3. pitch accents by gender and mode (adjusted):
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token by mode and gender.
    2. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per mode as if there were an equal number of male and female participants.
## Create tibble summarising  proportion of pitch accents per mode per speaker
pa_adj <- m_corpus %>%
  ## Count the number of acc_phon by speaker and mode
  group_by(speaker, stim, acc_phon) %>%
  summarise(nuc_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = nuc_count,
    values_fill = 0
  ) %>%
  ## convert the totals to proportion per stim.
  adorn_totals("col") %>%
  mutate(across(3:5, ~ (. / Total))) %>%
  select(-Total) %>%
  ## Convert stim column to mode.
  rename(mode = stim) %>%
  mutate(mode = substr(mode, 1, 3)) %>%
  ## Convert the values to proportion per mode
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "acc_phon") %>%
  group_by(speaker, mode, acc_phon) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  adorn_totals("col") %>%
  mutate(across(3:5, ~ (. / Total)),
    mode = factor(mode, levels = c("MDC", "MWH", "MYN", "MDQ"))
  ) %>%
  select(-Total) %>%
  as_tibble()

## Create tibble of pitch accents per speaker (adjusted).
pa_by_speaker_adj <- pa_adj %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "acc_phon") %>%
  select(-mode) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens
  ## per speaker.
  mutate(across(2:4, ~ round(. * 15, 0))) %>%
  select("speaker", "H*", "L*H", ">H*")

## Create tibble of pitch accents per mode (adjusted).
pa_by_mode_adj <- pa_adj %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "acc_phon") %>%
  select(-speaker) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens.
  mutate(across(2:4, ~ round(. * 15, 0))) %>%
  select("mode", "H*", "L*H", ">H*") %>%
  arrange(mode)

## Create tibble of pitch accents by gender and mode (adjusted).
pa_by_gender_adj <- pa_adj %>%
  ## Convert gender to speaker
  mutate(
    speaker = substr(speaker, 1, 1),
    speaker = factor(speaker, levels = unique(speaker))
  ) %>%
  rename(gender = speaker) %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "acc_phon") %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens
  ## per speaker.
  mutate(across(3:5, ~ if_else(
    gender == "F",
    round(. * 15, 0),
    ## project equal number of Male & Female speakers.
    round(. * 18, 0)
  ))) %>%
  select("mode", "gender", "H*", "L*H", ">H*") %>%
  arrange(mode)

It is clear that there is little relationship between the pitch accent and mode when the register tier is discounted. However, looking at the raw data for the phrase-level phonology, it looks like L% boundaries are more commonly associated with questions than declarative.

Therefore, it might be worth looking at the nuclear contour as a whole in this data set.

Contour by Mode and Gender

It appears that the male speakers are more likely to begin using L% across the question mode hierarchy more than the female speakers. There are not enough speakers, I believe, however, to justify this as a general conclusion, especially as it is only M8, M9, and M10 who do this.

Common contours
my_plot <- ggplot(
  nuc_contour_by_mode_adj %>%
    ## Uncount table for bar chart.
    pivot_longer(2:last_col(), names_to = "nuc_contour") %>%
    uncount(value) %>%
    mutate(
      nuc_contour =
        factor(
          nuc_contour,
          levels = c(
            "L*H %", "L*H L%", "L*H H%", "L*H HL%", ">H* L%", "H* L%"
          )
        )
    )
) +
  geom_bar(
    mapping = aes(
      x = mode,
      y = (after_stat(count)) / sum(after_stat(count)),
      fill = nuc_contour
    ),
    show.legend = F,
    colour = "black",
    position = position_dodge2(preserve = "single")
  ) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, limits = c(0, 0.28)) +
  facet_wrap(~nuc_contour, nrow = 2) +
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(fill = NA)) +
  ggtitle("Nuclear Contour by Sentence Mode (Adjusted, No Register)") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = nuc_contour_colours, name = "nuclear contour") +
  labs(x = "Mode", y = "tokens (%)") +
  theme(panel.border = element_rect(fill = NA)) +
  geom_text(
    aes(
      x = mode,
      y = (after_stat(count)) / sum(after_stat(count)),
      label = percent((after_stat(count)) / sum(after_stat(count)), 1)
    ),
    stat = "count",
    vjust = -0.75,
    size = 3
  )
ggsave(

my_plot

The overall pattern suggest that L% is more common among YNQs and and DCQs. However, I dont think that the L% is used to signal a question. I think that, as with the A&H corpus, L% is used when the speaker indicates there is a conflict of expectation of shared knowledge between the speaker and listener. Thus in questions like You live in the valley? and Do you live in the valley?, speaker can use the L% to indicate that the propositional content conflicts with what he or she had previously believed; i.e., it indicates surprise. In a reciprocal manner, in the declaratives of the A&H corpus (and here), the use of an L% indicates that the speaker is indicating surprise that the listener does not already share the knowledge. (i.e.Where do you live?I live in the valley [L%] (and I assumed you already knew that / and you should know that already.) Perhaps the best way to think of this is as the surprise~redundancy strategy, with the conflict of expectations expressing redundancy in the declaratives (This should not be news to you.) and surprise in the questions (I did not know this at all!).

The results give the impression that this is a feature of male rather than female speech. However, only three out of the five male speakers do this, so it is unlikely to be a features of male speech. More likely, different speakers interpreted the motivation behind the prompt statement and their response, in terms of the intonational phonology, reflects whether or not they chose to use a surprise/redundancy falling boundary.

BGLMM analysis

Likelihood of H%.

Complete separation issue

  • GLMER cannot correctly estimate the CIs of H:L for MDC and MWH since there are no instances of H for either level, leading to a problem know as complete separation.

To resolve this issue, I have used the blme package, which uses Maximum a posteriori estimation for linear and generalized linear mixed-effects models in a Bayesian setting (documentation).

We can use this to impose zero-mean Normal priors on the fixed effects (a 4 4 diagonal matrix with diagonal elements equal to 9, for variances of 9 or standard deviations of 3)

(http://bbolker.github.io/mixedmodels-misc/ecostats_chap.html#digression-complete-separation)

(directed from https://bbolker.github.io/mixedmodels-misc/glmmFAQ.html#penalizationhandling-complete-separation)

m_corpus_is_H_boundary <- m_corpus %>%
  ## treat HL% as for purpose of % vs H%
  mutate(`H%` = str_replace(fin_phon, "HL\\%", "H%")) %>%
  mutate(`H%` = factor(`H%` == "H%", level = c(F, T)))
fin_phon_model_H_or_not <- bglmer(
  `H%` ~ mode + gender + (1 | speaker) + (1 | prompt),
  data = m_corpus_is_H_boundary,
  family = binomial(link = "logit"),
  fixef.prior = normal(),
  ## change optimizer to avoid convergence errors
  control = glmerControl(
    optimizer = "optimx",
    calc.derivs = FALSE,
    optCtrl = list(
      method = "nlminb",
      starttests = FALSE,
      kkt = FALSE
    )
  )
)

fin_phon_model_H_or_not <- optimizeModel(fin_phon_model_H_or_not, reject_nm = F)

Adjusted Data

The raw data is unbalanced since the number of utterances per target speaker varies slightly. For some speakers, there are no repetitions of some target utterances. Therefore, the data has been adjusted to project an estimated balanced number of tokens per speaker per target utterance.

Firstly a tibble is created summarising the proportion of pitch accents per mode per speaker. This is done in three initial stages:

  1. Count the number of phonological tokens per stimulus per speaker.
  2. Convert the counts to proportion per stimulus per speaker.
  3. Convert the proportion per stimulus per speaker to a proportion per stimulus per mode.

From this table summary tables are created:

  1. pitch accents per speaker (adjusted)
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token per speaker.
    2. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per speaker.
  2. pitch accents per mode (adjusted):
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token per mode.
    2. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per mode
  3. pitch accents by gender and mode (adjusted):
    1. Calculate the sum all proportions per token by mode and gender.
  1. Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens per mode as if there were an equal numnber of male and female participants.

    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens
  ## per speaker.
  mutate(across(3:8, ~ if_else(gender == "F",
    round(. * 15, 0),
    ## project equal number of Male & Female speakers.
    round(. * 18, 0)
  ))) %>%
  select("mode", "gender", "H*", ">H*", "^[L*]H", "L*H", "L*^[H]", "^[L*H]") %>%
  arrange(mode)


## Create tibble of pitch accents by gender and mode (adjusted).
##
pa_by_mode_speaker_adj <- pa_adj %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.

  pivot_wider(
    names_from = acc_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to integer based on ideal number of by-speaker tokens.
  mutate(across(3:last_col(), ~ round(. * 16))) %>%
  ## re-order the columns
  select("mode", "speaker", "H*", ">H*", "^[L*]H", "L*H", "L*^[H]", "^[L*H]") %>%

Boundary Tone Analysis

fin_phon_adj <- m_corpus %>%
  mutate(fin_phon = str_replace_all(fin_phon, "\\[|\\]|\\^", "")) %>%
  mutate(fin_phon = factor(fin_phon, levels = unique(fin_phon))) %>%
  ## Count the number of fin_phon by speaker and mode
  group_by(speaker, stim, fin_phon) %>%
  summarise(nuc_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = fin_phon,
    values_from = nuc_count,
    values_fill = 0
  ) %>%
  ## convert the totals to proportion per stim.
  adorn_totals("col") %>%
  mutate(across(3:(last_col() - 1), ~ (. / Total))) %>%
  select(-Total) %>%
  ## Convert stim column to mode.
  rename(mode = stim) %>%
  mutate(mode = substr(mode, 1, 3)) %>%
  ## Convert the values to proportion per mode
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "fin_phon") %>%
  group_by(speaker, mode, fin_phon) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = fin_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  adorn_totals("col") %>%
  mutate(across(3:(last_col() - 1), ~ (. / Total)),
    mode = factor(mode, levels = c("MDC", "MWH", "MYN", "MDQ"))
  ) %>%
  select(-Total) %>%
  as_tibble()

## Create tibble of final boundaries per mode (adjusted).
fin_phon_by_mode_adj <- fin_phon_adj %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "fin_phon") %>%
  select(-c(speaker)) %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = fin_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens.
  mutate(across(2:last_col(), ~ round(. * 15, 0))) %>%
  arrange(mode)

## Create tibble of final boundaries  by gender and mode (adjusted).
fin_phon_by_gender_adj <- fin_phon_adj %>%
  ## Convert speaker to gender
  mutate(
    speaker = substr(speaker, 1, 1),
    speaker = factor(speaker, levels = unique(speaker))
  ) %>%
  rename(gender = speaker) %>%
  ## Get the sum of all token proportions per speaker.
  pivot_longer(3:last_col(), names_to = "fin_phon") %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = fin_phon,
    values_from = value,
    values_fill = 0,
    values_fn = ~ sum(.)
  ) %>%
  ## Convert proportions to an integer based on an ideal total number of tokens
  ## per speaker.
  mutate(across(3:last_col(), ~ if_else(gender == "F",
    round(. * 15, 0),
    ## project equal number of Male & Female speakers.
    round(. * 18, 0)
  ))) %>%
  arrange(mode)

BGLMM Analysis

H-Register and Mode

m_corpus_h_reg <- m_corpus %>%
  select(prompt, speaker, gender, nuc_H_reg, mode)


h_reg_model <- bglmer(
  nuc_H_reg ~ mode + gender + (1 | speaker) + (1 | prompt),
  data = m_corpus_h_reg,
  family = binomial(link = "logit"),
  fixef.prior = normal()
)


h_reg_model <- optimizeModel(h_reg_model, reject_nm = F)
LRT
write <- "output/Mode_PA_GLMM"

)

## Load Corpus
m_corpus <- get_m_corpus("../../4_data/m_corpus.csv") %>%
  ## Keep only factors needed for analysis
  select(
    speaker,
    gender,
    mode,
    utt_mean_f0,
    utt_slope,
    phr_phon,
    acc_phon,
    fin_phon,
    prompt
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    ## h_start = phrases beginning with a high boundary or H* in first foot.
    h_start = if_else(!is.na((str_extract(phr_phon, "%H|\\^\\[%H|% H\\*"))),
      "H start",
      "no H start"
    ),
    h_start = factor(h_start, levels = c("H start", "no H start")),
    ## Remove register tier identifers from fin_phon. (See Chapter 7.5.2.2.)
    fin_phon = factor(str_replace_all(fin_phon, "\\^|\\[|\\]", ""),
      levels = c("%", "L%")
    )
  )

B.2. Utterance slope f0(t)

utt_slope_full_mdl <- lmer(
  utt_slope ~
    mode
    + h_start
    + acc_phon
    + fin_phon
    + gender
    + (1 + mode | speaker)
    + (1 | prompt),
  data = m_corpus,
  control = lmerControl(
    optimizer = "optimx",
    calc.derivs = F,
    optCtrl = list(
      method = "nlminb",
      starttests = F,
      kkt = F
    )
  )
)

utt_slope_full_mdl <- optimizeModel(utt_slope_full_mdl, verbose = F)

utt_slope_full_mdl <- update(
  utt_slope_full_mdl,
  data = m_corpus %>% filter(abs(scale(resid(utt_slope_full_mdl))) <= 3)
)
